</li><!-- #comment-## -->
<li id="comment-524429" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1"><article id="div-comment-524429" class="comment-body media"><footer class="comment-meta media-left"></footer><!-- .comment-meta -->
    <div class="comment-content media-body">
        <div class="comment-author vcard">
            <div class="comment-metadata">
            <cite class="fn">Barbara Carlson</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>
        </div><!-- .comment-author -->
<time datetime="2020-03-01T23:18:36-05:00">March 1, 2020 at 11:18 pm</time> 
            </div><!-- .comment-metadata -->
<p>I have an at least 139 year old page of music, no lyrics, entitled The Star-Spangled Banner, Favorite American Air, which is number 43 on page 38 in Bertini’s Instruction Book for the Pianoforte, Rudiments of Music, and it is all contained in a hand-stitched folder with a girl’s name and the date 1881 penned on the front. I bought this item at an antique store in Phoenix, Arizona in 2016. I have done extensive research on the girl who presumably made the folder and have traced its journey from Cornwall, England 1881 to the store in which I found it. I thought I would try to get the folder and it’s contents to the girl’s descendants. Because of its age, though,I am writing here to see if there is any historical significance to the single sheet of music described above since I have been unable to find any reference to another. It’s in pretty good shape, the whole thing is, but without proper preservation I don’t know how long it will last. </p>
<p>Thank you,<br />
Barbara Carlson<br />
Phoenix, Arizona</p>

    </div><!-- .comment-content -->
</article><!-- .comment-body -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
        </ol><!-- .comment-list -->

        
    

